      [1;34m"body"[m[1;37m:[m [32m"**Actionable comments posted: 16**\n\n<details>\n<summary>🧹 Nitpick comments (8)</summary><blockquote>\n\n<details>\n<summary>static/manifest.json (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`10-23`: _🩺 Stability & Availability_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**Self-host PWA icons instead of pointing to `raw.githubusercontent.com`.**\n\nIcons sourced from a third-party CDN (raw.githubusercontent.com) risk broken installs if the branch/path changes, GitHub is unreachable, or CORS/content-type headers differ from what browsers expect for maskable icons. Serve icons from `/static/` alongside the manifest for reliability.\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@static/manifest.json` around lines 10 - 23, The manifest icons are still\npointing to raw.githubusercontent.com, so update the icons array in\nmanifest.json to use locally hosted assets under /static/ instead of remote\nURLs. Replace the current external src values with self-hosted paths for both\nthe maskable and regular icons, keeping the same sizes/type/purpose entries so\nthe PWA can install reliably without depending on GitHub.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:b83d34298ff6ffc339430f94 -->\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>static/sw.js (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`8-16`: _📐 Maintainability & Code Quality_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**Missing cache versioning cleanup and update activation.**\n\nNo `activate` handler purges caches from prior `CACHE_NAME` values, so bumping the version later leaves stale caches around indefinitely. Also missing `skipWaiting()`/`clients.claim()` delays new SW activation until all tabs close.\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@static/sw.js` around lines 8 - 16, The service worker in sw.js only handles\ninstall and fetch, so old CACHE_NAME entries are never removed and new versions\nstay waiting too long. Add an activate handler that deletes caches not matching\nthe current CACHE_NAME, and update the install flow to call skipWaiting() so the\nnew worker can take over immediately; also have activate call clients.claim() to\ncontrol existing tabs after activation. Use the existing CACHE_NAME constant and\nthe sw.js event listeners to wire this in.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:e50f1a13e3c2cce3ac9279e7 -->\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>debug_site.py (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`8-19`: _📐 Maintainability & Code Quality_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**Include `/download` in the smoke test.**\n\nThis helper skips the new download page, so a regression in the PR’s main user-facing route could still report success. Add `/download` if this script is meant to validate the public routes.\n\n\n\n\n\n<details>\n<summary>♻️ Proposed fix</summary>\n\n```diff\n-    routes = ['/', '/release-notes', '/faq']\n+    routes = ['/', '/download', '/release-notes', '/faq']\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@debug_site.py` around lines 8 - 19, The smoke test in the route-check loop is\nmissing the new public `/download` page, so a failure there would not be\ndetected. Update the `routes` list in `debug_site.py` to include `/download`\nalongside the existing public routes, keeping the validation logic in the same\nloop so `client.get(route)` covers the new page too.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:5869c4f2ad0e6f70bfb1c308 -->\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>bot_polling.py (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`34-38`: _📐 Maintainability & Code Quality_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _💤 Low value_\n\n**Broad exception handling.**\n\nCatching bare `Exception` in the forward/poll loops is acceptable here for resilience (prevents the loop from crashing on transient errors), but consider logging the exception type for easier debugging.\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@bot_polling.py` around lines 34 - 38, In the forward/poll error handling\ninside the polling loop, keep the broad Exception catches for resilience but\nupdate the logging in the relevant exception blocks in bot_polling.py to include\nthe exception type alongside the message. Use the existing forward/webhook retry\nblock and the main polling exception block as the touchpoints, and ensure the\nprinted/logged output shows both the exception class name and the error text for\neasier debugging.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:327bb173963b39bd4f208b68 -->\n\n_Source: Linters/SAST tools_\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>run_all.sh (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`11-18`: _🩺 Stability & Availability_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**No fallback to polling if webhook setup fails.**\n\n`setup_webhook.py` is invoked synchronously with no exit-status check. If it fails (e.g., network error, invalid token), the script silently continues without either a working webhook or the polling fallback — the bot ends up with no way to receive updates.\n\nConsider checking the exit status and falling back to polling:\n```diff\n if [ -n \"$TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN\" ] && [ -n \"$WEBHOOK_URL\" ]; then\n     echo \"Configurando Webhook de Telegram...\"\n-    python3 setup_webhook.py\n+    python3 setup_webhook.py || { echo \"Webhook setup failed, falling back to polling...\"; python3 bot_polling.py & }\n else\n```\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@run_all.sh` around lines 11 - 18, The Telegram startup flow in run_all.sh\nonly launches polling when TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN or WEBHOOK_URL is missing, so a\nfailed setup_webhook.py run leaves no update mechanism running. Update the\nwebhook branch to check the exit status of setup_webhook.py and, if it fails,\nstart bot_polling.py as a fallback; keep the behavior consistent with the\nexisting polling path and preserve the current Telegram setup logic.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:24add9c7145aea721503b91d -->\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>lib/auth.py (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`9-13`: _📐 Maintainability & Code Quality_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**Narrow the bare `except` in `verify_token`.**\n\nCatching all exceptions masks real bugs (e.g., wrong secret type) alongside expected `jwt.ExpiredSignatureError`/`InvalidTokenError`. Prefer catching `jwt.PyJWTError` explicitly.\n\n<details>\n<summary>♻️ Proposed fix</summary>\n\n```diff\n def verify_token(token, secret):\n     try:\n         return jwt.decode(token, secret, algorithms=['HS256'])\n-    except:\n+    except jwt.PyJWTError:\n         return None\n```\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@lib/auth.py` around lines 9 - 13, The `verify_token` function currently uses\na bare `except`, which hides unexpected failures along with invalid JWT cases.\nUpdate `verify_token` to catch `jwt.PyJWTError` explicitly (or the specific JWT\nexceptions you expect) while keeping the `jwt.decode` behavior unchanged, so\nonly token-related errors return `None` and real bugs can surface.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:7fa02d10282f250ca2db4e85 -->\n\n_Source: Linters/SAST tools_\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>templates/download.html (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`33-34`: _🎯 Functional Correctness_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**Hardcoded Spanish text bypasses the translations system.**\n\nUnlike the rest of this page (and `index.html`), these strings are hardcoded Spanish rather than pulled from `translations`, breaking localization on the download flow for non-Spanish users.\n\n<details>\n<summary>♻️ Proposed direction</summary>\n\n```diff\n-            <p style=\"margin-bottom: var(--space-2);\">Versión {{ download_info.direct_download.version }} para {{ download_info.direct_download.platform }}</p>\n+            <p style=\"margin-bottom: var(--space-2);\">{{ translations.download_version_for.format(version=download_info.direct_download.version, platform=download_info.direct_download.platform) }}</p>\n```\nSimilarly move the four \"Requirements Card\" list items into `translations.*` keys.\n</details>\n\n\n\n\n\nAlso applies to: 85-98\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@templates/download.html` around lines 33 - 34, The download page still\nhardcodes Spanish strings in the direct download section, which bypasses the\nlocalization system. Update the template to read these labels from the existing\ntranslations object instead of literal text, following the same pattern used in\nindex.html and the rest of download.html. Also move the four Requirements Card\nlist items into translations.* keys and wire the template to use those keys so\nthe download flow is fully localized.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:fbf7b5e4cd8eec07c1ed9809 -->\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>lib/build.py (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`11-27`: _🔒 Security & Privacy_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _💤 Low value_\n\n**Extract the shared `details.xml` parser** `parse_details_xml` is duplicated in `lib/BuildThread.py`, so metadata keys and aliases can drift between the two implementations.\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@lib/build.py` around lines 11 - 27, The shared details.xml parsing logic is\nduplicated in parse_details_xml across lib/build.py and lib/BuildThread.py,\nwhich can cause metadata fields and defaults to drift over time. Extract the\nparser into a single shared helper and make both callers use that one\nimplementation, keeping the same returned keys/aliases and fallback defaults in\nparse_details_xml so the metadata shape stays consistent.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:0c5cc5358a77b0d1e1b0749c -->\n\n_Source: Linters/SAST tools_\n\n</blockquote></details>\n\n</blockquote></details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for all review comments with AI agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nInline comments:\nIn `@bot_polling.py`:\n- Around line 20-26: Add client-side timeouts to the Telegram API requests in\nbot_polling.py so the polling loop cannot hang indefinitely. Update the\ndeleteWebhook call and the getUpdates request in the polling loop to pass an\nexplicit requests timeout, while keeping the existing Telegram long-poll timeout\nparameter in the URL. Use the request-building logic around TOKEN,\ndeleteWebhook, and getUpdates as the fix location.\n\nIn `@faq_main.md`:\n- Around line 150-161: The final fenced block in the markdown snippet is\nunlabeled, which causes lint failures. Update the fence in the relevant example\nso it is explicitly labeled as text (or another appropriate language) while\nkeeping the content unchanged. Use the markdown block in faq_main.md as the\ntarget to locate and fix the fence.\n\nIn `@lib/auth.py`:\n- Line 6: The token payload timestamp generation in the auth flow uses a naive\nUTC datetime, which triggers deprecation warnings in newer Python versions.\nUpdate the payload creation in the token-building logic to use timezone-aware\nUTC timestamps via the datetime import that includes timezone, and apply it\nconsistently for both the exp and iat values so the authentication code remains\ncompatible and warning-free.\n\nIn `@lib/build.py`:\n- Around line 29-45: The temporary directories created by build_project (and the\nsame pattern in extract_project_from_zip) are never removed, so disk usage can\ngrow indefinitely on long-running servers. Update build_project to manage the\nmkdtemp path with cleanup after compiler.run completes or fails, using a\ntry/finally flow around the FlangCompiler invocation and any returned result\nhandling. Apply the same cleanup approach in extract_project_from_zip so both\nhelpers consistently delete their temporary directories even when exceptions\noccur.\n\nIn `@lib/config.py`:\n- Around line 6-7: The SECRET_KEY and JWT_SECRET fallback literals in the config\nsetup are insecure and should not be used silently. Update the configuration\nlogic in the config module so that the app requires explicit values for these\nsettings in production, either by raising an error during startup when\nSECRET_KEY or JWT_SECRET is missing or by emitting a very loud warning only in\nnon-production defaults. Keep the change localized to the config constants that\nread os.environ.get for SECRET_KEY and JWT_SECRET so the startup behavior is\neasy to find and verify.\n\nIn `@lib/github.py`:\n- Around line 13-16: The fallback in the GitHub release lookup is checking the\nwrong case, so it never retries after a token-caused 404. Update the logic in\nthe release-fetching code in lib/github.py so the unauthenticated retry happens\nwhen a token was actually provided and the authenticated request returns 404,\nnot when token is absent. Use the existing request flow around the\nlatest-releases call to keep the public-repo fallback behavior intact and avoid\nthe redundant duplicate request.\n\nIn `@run_all.sh`:\n- Line 5: The gunicorn launch in run_all.sh assumes PORT is always set, which\ncan cause binding failures when it is empty. Update the startup command to use\nthe same fallback behavior as bot_polling.py by defaulting PORT to 5000 when\nunset, so the app:app server starts reliably through the gunicorn invocation.\n\nIn `@setup_webhook.py`:\n- Around line 23-31: The `requests.post` call in `setup_webhook.py` lacks a\ntimeout, which can leave the webhook setup hanging indefinitely and block\nstartup in `run_all.sh`. Update the `setWebhook` request in the setup flow to\nuse a reasonable timeout and keep the existing success/error handling around\n`response.json()` and the `except Exception as e` path.\n\nIn `@static/sw.js`:\n- Around line 1-10: The install flow in self.addEventListener('install')\ncurrently uses cache.addAll on the assets array, so one failed request\n(especially the external Font Awesome URL) rejects the whole service worker\ninstall. Update the caching logic in the install handler to cache each asset\nindependently with per-asset error handling, so a failure in one resource does\nnot block activation of the service worker or offline support for the rest of\nthe app shell.\n\nIn `@templates/admin_reports.html`:\n- Around line 1-36: The admin reports page currently exposes sensitive reporter\ndetails and its resolve action is an unprotected POST. Update the route/template\npair behind the admin reports view so only authenticated admins can access the\ndata rendered in admin_reports.html, and add CSRF protection to the resolve form\nusing the existing admin form handling path. Use the admin reports route and the\nreport resolve endpoint as the primary places to enforce auth and token\nvalidation.\n\nIn `@templates/base.html`:\n- Line 5: The 