t code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@run_all.sh` at line 28, The gunicorn launch in run_all.sh uses an unquoted\n${PORT:-5000} in the --bind argument, which Shellcheck flags for unsafe word\nsplitting. Update the exec gunicorn command to quote the bind value while\nkeeping the same default port behavior, so the PORT expansion is treated as a\nsingle argument.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:b676cb304d0c5be6b9468d0e -->\n\n_Source: Linters/SAST tools_\n\n</blockquote></details>\n<details>\n<summary>app.py (1)</summary><blockquote>\n\n`1591-1599`: _📐 Maintainability & Code Quality_ | _🔵 Trivial_ | _⚡ Quick win_\n\n**Drop the self-import; call `init_db()` directly.**\n\n`from app import init_db` imports the module into itself. `init_db` is already defined in scope at this point, so the import is redundant. Worse, when this file is executed as `__main__` (e.g. `python app.py`), `from app import ...` triggers a *second* execution of the whole module under the name `app`, duplicating side effects. Just invoke the already-defined function.\n\n\n\n\n\n<details>\n<summary>♻️ Proposed change</summary>\n\n```diff\n with app.app_context():\n     try:\n-        from app import init_db\n         init_db()\n         print(\"Base de datos inicializada correctamente.\")\n     except Exception as e:\n         print(f\"Error al inicializar base de datos: {e}\")\n```\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nIn `@app.py` around lines 1591 - 1599, The database initialization block is\nperforming a self-import inside the app context, which is redundant and can\nre-execute the module when app.py runs as __main__. Remove the `from app import\ninit_db` import and call the already-defined `init_db()` directly in the\nexisting initialization block, keeping the try/except and log messages intact.\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<!-- cr-comment:v1:040e7eff77ede760f9798f60 -->\n\n</blockquote></details>\n\n</blockquote></details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>🤖 Prompt for all review comments with AI agents</summary>\n\n```\nVerify each finding against current code. Fix only still-valid issues, skip the\nrest with a brief reason, keep changes minimal, and validate.\n\nInline comments:\nIn `@app.py`:\n- Around line 1152-1171: The Telegram webhook handler has outbound requests in\nthe callback flow that can hang without a timeout. Update the `requests.post`\ncalls in the callback-action block, including `answerCallbackQuery`,\n`editMessageText`, and the final `answerCallbackQuery`, to pass an explicit\n`timeout`. Keep the change localized to the callback handling logic around `cq`,\n`new_text`, and `send_telegram_message` so all Telegram API calls fail fast\ninstead of blocking the worker.\n- Line 1130: The Telegram payload write in app.py is using json.dumps(data)\nwithout importing json, which causes the insert path to fail. Add the missing\njson import near the top of app.py and keep the payload serialization in the\ninsert logic so the telegram_messages record can store the raw JSON payload when\nthe database write runs.\n- Around line 1112-1172: The telegram_webhook route currently trusts\nrequest.json without verifying that the request באמת came from Telegram, so add\nauthentication at the start of telegram_webhook using the\nX-Telegram-Bot-Api-Secret-Token header and TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET before any\ncallback_query or owner logic runs. Reject unauthorized requests with a 403\nresponse, then keep the existing resolve/contact handling and\nsend_telegram_message flow unchanged so only validated Telegram deliveries can\ntrigger those actions.\n\n---\n\nNitpick comments:\nIn `@app.py`:\n- Around line 1591-1599: The database initialization block is performing a\nself-import inside the app context, which is re